          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p>
                                        <placeName>London</placeName>
                                        <date>31<hi rend="sup">st</hi> March 1845</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>Reverend and dear Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I have before me your highly esteemed<lb/> favors
                                                  <date>30<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Decr. and Jany.
                                                  15<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date> the latter to the
                                        care of <persName>Mr Solis</persName><lb/> who I believe has
                                        left <placeName>England</placeName> for
                                                  <placeName>Holland</placeName>. The first
                                        sight<lb/> of this gentleman operated upon my feelings as if
                                        he were a<lb/> connecting link between us two gratifying to
                                        me to converse<lb/> with one so intimate with yourself.
                                        Independent of his own<lb/> merits, he bringing a letter of
                                        Introduction from you <sic>insured</sic> him a<lb/> warm
                                        reception at my hands and he certainly has made a<lb/>
                                        favorable impression upon me and my family. I could
                                        have<lb/> wished to have paid him more attention than he has
                                        afforded me<lb/> the opportunity of doing, but hope when he
                                        returns to <placeName>England</placeName><lb/> I shall see
                                        more of him. He has lunched twice with me at my<lb/> office
                                        in the city and dined once with us in <placeName>upper
                                                  Bedford</placeName> place<lb/> where I hope I
                                        shall soon have the pleasure of his company<lb/> again and
                                        again.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">The Jewish Chronicle No 14 contains nearly
                                        the<lb/> whole of my letter to you of the <date>10<hi
                                                  rend="sup">th</hi> Septr</date> and had the
                                        paper<lb/> been stamped I would have sent you by this
                                        oppory. I think<lb/> and I hope you'll be satisfied <del>in
                                                  the</del> with the manner I do not<lb/> let <hi
                                                  rend="underline">you</hi> mention a name, not even
                                        that of <persName>Mr Carillon</persName><lb/> and you'll see
                                        that I have suppressed personal matter.<lb/> The publication
                                        of my letter has made a great sensation and<lb/> you'll be
                                        surprised to learn that it is now being translated<lb/> into
                                        [Hebrew], into German and into French, this I tell you <hi
                                                  rend="underline">confidentially</hi><lb/> I have
                                        nothing to do with its reprint into the Holy Tongue and<lb/>
                                        English, not so with the German and French, the letter
                                        will<lb/> appear in the Archive. <del>In</del> The last No
                                        of the Voice 99<lb/> headed "Secession and Retrocession"
                                        you'll not comprehend well<lb/> till you obtain the J
                                        Chronicle, the next No of which will</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>contain a reply to any letter to the Occident. The part
                                        improved<lb/> in my saying that burial was denied to
                                                  <persName>Mr H Montefiore</persName>. On<lb/> this
                                        head the "Voice" reminds me of the information he gave me
                                        on<lb/> that point, but he knows not that in consequence of
                                        that<lb/> very information I called on the <hi
                                                  rend="underline">nearest</hi> relations of the
                                        deceased<lb/> before I sent my letter to the Press. I knew
                                        that there were<lb/> some degrading terms annexed to the
                                        offer of burial which<lb/> the husband spurned and which
                                        terms had I touched upon<lb/> I must have made the pictures
                                        still darker! Three<lb/> years ago, in "Rejected Letters" I
                                        bring the same charges, denial<lb/> of burial, without
                                        naming the degrading terms. I have<lb/> thought it right to
                                        give you this information for the <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >present</hi>,<lb/> my <sic>defence</sic> will
                                        appear when I have seen the charges.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">And now, my dear Sir to your favor <date>30
                                                  Decr.</date> which<lb/> needs but little by way of
                                        reply as I have no wish to keep up the<lb/> bell of
                                        Discussion on the very few points of disagreement and I
                                        feel<lb/> assured that even these few would be diminished
                                        could we discuss<lb/> the matter colloquially. I note all
                                        you say about <persName>Mr Marks</persName> and with<lb/> me
                                        the explanation rests. I was pleased to see his Sermon on
                                        the<lb/> Shemary[?] in the Occidentâ€”your Note has been
                                        transferred to the<lb/> Voice. No Sir! Your
                                                  <sic>candour</sic> does not offend me, as friends
                                        we<lb/> must agree to differ. Thanks for your
                                        congratulations on my<lb/> daughter's matrimonial
                                        engagement. A few words will suffice<lb/> in reply to your
                                        last. Thanks for the portions you gave of my long<lb/>
                                        letter in No 22 and for the insertion of the whole of the
                                        short one.<lb/> Your appended remarks to my communications
                                        do not call for reply<lb/> but you have my thanks for
                                        offering me the oppory. to do so if I wish.<lb/> Do not
                                        hesitate a moment when you wish to give any friend a letter
                                        of introduction<lb/> to me. That the Almighty may accord you
                                        all your wishes in the<lb/> sincere prayer of My dear Sir.
                                        Yours very Truly</p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">
                                        <persName role="author">Benj Ekin[?]</persName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>I have given to a friend some of the Jewish Chronicle<lb/> No 14[?]
                                        who promises to send them to <placeName>New York</placeName>
                                        to be<lb/> forwarded to your address <persName role="author"
                                                  >B. E.</persName></p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>The Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <placeName>118 South fourth Street</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">
                                        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                              </p>
